Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Portman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (West Midlands): status name from Middle English <i>portman</i> ‘townsman, burgher, citizen’ (Old English <i>portmann</i>).","Dutch: from <i>poort</i> ‘gate’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, an occupational name for a gatekeeper or a topographic name for someone who lived near the gates of a walled town. In North America, this surname may also be an altered form of the more common variant <b>Poortman</b>.","Americanized form of German   Portmann  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sportsman","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of Flemish <b>Sportmans</b>: patronymic from <b>Poortman</b> (see   Portman   2), genitivized by the initial <i>s</i> (from <i>des</i> ‘of the’) and the suffix <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Portmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Helmut, Franz, Hansi, Kurt.","North German: occupational name for a gatekeeper, from Middle Low German <i>port(e)</i> ‘gate’ (from Latin <i>porta</i>) + <i>man</i> ‘man’, or a topographic name for someone who lived near the gates of a fortified town. Compare   Porter  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":51,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Portman was born in 1404, in Somerset, England, his father, Thomas Portman, was 28 and his mother, Mrs. Thomas Portman, was 26. He married Christian Orchard before 1440, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1474, at the age of 70, and was buried in Taunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1404–1474":"1404–1474","1407–1472":"1407–1472","1445–1521":"1445–1521","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1378–Female":"1378–Surnud","1404":"1404","7 May 1472":"7. mai 1472","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1521":"1521","before 1440":"enne 1440","1376":"1376","1474":"1474","1472":"1472","1407":"1407","Middle Temple, London, Middlesex, England":"London The Temple, Middlesex, England","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","England":"England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1404–1474":"1404–1474","1407–1472":"1407–1472","1445–1521":"1445–1521","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1378–Female":"1378–Kuollut","1404":"1404","7 May 1472":"7. toukokuuta 1472","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1521":"1521","before 1440":"ennen vuotta 1440","1376":"1376","1474":"1474","1472":"1472","1407":"1407","Middle Temple, London, Middlesex, England":"London The Temple, Middlesex, England","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","England":"England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1404–1474":"1404–1474","1407–1472":"1407–1472","1445–1521":"1445–1521","1376–Male":"1376–Décédé","1378–Female"